@edimoraru @Paratron @SmartBear True, but it's also the possibilities of the tool that can limit the ways to collaborate. 
Jira has a bias towards expressing everything in issues, issues can only be owned (assigned) to one person,... 
These are decisions made by the tool, not by your process.

@looneysquash @starbuxman Agree, but with small PRs there is usually not that much extra information anyway.

Also, for how long in the future are having individual commits useful.

The code is in the end what matters, not how it came to be.

I got bitten today by a nasty #JavaScript thing:

const handler = async () =&gt; {
  try {
    return request();
  } catch (err) {
   // I wanted to handle request errors here
   // but since request returns a promise
   // they won't get caught
  }
};

The important change to make it work is:

-    return request();
+    return await request();

